summary: The document comprises memorandums from July 1968 and June 1969, focusing on the investigation of William Wayne Dalzell in relation to the John F. Kennedy assassination, particularly the Garrison investigation. It outlines requests for traces on Dalzell from Ethiopian Station and desk traces, which did not uncover any information beyond what was already in his 201 file. The memorandums shed light on Dalzell's contacts in Addis Ababa in 1956 and illustrate the procedural dynamics of intelligence operations during historical investigations.
key_findings: William Wayne Dalzell was investigated in connection with the Garrison investigation into the John F. Kennedy assassination.
Requests for traces on Dalzell from Ethiopian Station and desk traces provided no new information beyond his 201 file.
Dalzell's interactions with the station in Addis Ababa in 1956 were noted.
The memorandums exemplify the methods of intelligence gathering and sharing in historical investigations.
